Introduction

Ive chosen the two datasets hate_crimes and partisan_lean_state from the fivethirtyeight package. My major is government and I chose to find data in this package because it contains a lot of interesting political subjects. Im especially interested in the Cook Partisan Voting Index (PVI) from the partisan_lean_state and the median income from hate_crimes to see if there is a difference in the PVI (as a proxy for political polarization) across different incomes. PVI scores are a measurement of how democratic or republican a state is, meaning that a lower PVI score indicates that the voters in the state are more split between the two parties. I expect that there is less political polarization the higher the median income in the state is. My merging variable is state.

The partisan_lean_state data have 50 rows/distinct IDs for the 50 states and 3 variables in total. The hate_crimes dataset have 51 rows/distinct IDs, because it includes the District of Columbia as a state. It contains 13 variables in total. I chose a full join, even though I know that there isnt any data on DC in the partisan_lean_state dataset. This means that DC will get NAs for the two variables that the partisan_lean_state adds. I will to keep it, because I might want to do some visualizations only with the data the from hate_crimes and then I might as well keep DC for more data. The joined data contains 51 rows and 15 columns.

For this part of the wrangling, I used a lot of different function to explore the dataset. First I saw only the republican states of the dataset, to look for any patterns. Then I filtered the dataset to only look at the variables that Im most interested in. Then I arranged the dataset descending after the PVI score. The last two lines of code makes a new variable called metro_to_trump, which shows the relationship between share of urban population and share of Trump votes.

Visualizing

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(mydataset, aes(x = pvi_amount)) + geom_histogram(bins = 15, 
    color = "black", fill = "white") + geom_vline(xintercept = 16.94, 
    linetype = "dashed", color = "red") + ggtitle("PVI Amount") + 
    xlab("PVI score") + ylab("Count")

My plot 1 is a visual presentation of the variable PVI score. I shows a histogram of the distribution of the variable and I added a red dotted line to show the average PVI score across states. PVI score is a measurement of how strongly a state lean towards the Republican or Democratic party, so 0 is the highest degree of polarization. The histogram shows that the PVI scores are generally either relatively low or between 10 and 30.

ggplot(mydataset, aes(median_house_inc, pvi_amount)) + geom_point(aes(color = pvi_party)) + 
    scale_color_manual(values = c(R = "red", D = "blue")) + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
    ggtitle("Income vs. polarization") + xlab("Median income") + 
    ylab("PVI score")

Plot 2 is a scatterplot to show the linear relationship between income and PVI score/polarization. I expected that the higher income a state have, the lower degree of polarization. There is a small tendency towards that relationship, but it is definitely not a strong relationship. As an extra feature, I added the party color to the dots to see if there is any pattern within the two different parties. It doesnt seem like it though.

ggplot(mydataset, aes(x = pvi_party, fill = pvi_party)) + geom_bar(aes(y = pvi_amount), 
    stat = "summary", fun = mean) + scale_fill_manual(values = c(R = "red", 
    D = "blue")) + coord_flip() + theme(legend.position = "none")

For plot 3, I wanted to investigate whether there is a difference between the PVI scores, and thus the degree of political polarization. This graph shows that republican states have a higher average PVI score than democratic states does. That means, that generally speaking, republican states are less polarized then democratic states (because 0 is the highest degree of polarization). I tried to remove the NA-bar, with both na-rm= TRUE and na.omit, but none of them worked.

Concluding Remarks

I didnt find the relationship between PVI score and income as I expected, even though the graph shows a small tendency in that direction. But I found another interesting fact that might be worth to look into more detail with, namely that republican states seems to be less split than democratic states.
